=> Azure API Management (APIM)

    -> Overview:
        -> Azure API Management is a fully managed service provided by Microsoft that helps organizations create, publish, secure, and monitor APIs in a structured way.
        -> In simple terms: APIM acts like a middle layer (gateway) between Clients (apps, users, developers) and Backend services (your actual APIs, microservices, databases).
        -> Why Do We Need API Management:
            -> Imagine you built multiple APIs Login API, Payment API, Order API.
            -> If you expose them directly:
                -> No proper security
                -> No rate control
                -> No monitoring
                -> No central access point
            -> That’s where APIM helps. APIM solves these problems:
                -> Secures APIs (API keys, OAuth, JWT)
                -> Tracks usage (analytics, logs)
                -> Controls traffic (rate limiting, throttling)
                -> Provides developer onboarding (portal)

    -> Core Concept in APIM:
        -> API(One API = Many operations): An API is a collection of operations (endpoints). Example:
            -> /getUser
            -> /createOrder
            -> /makePayment

        -> Product: A Product is a bundle (collection) of APIs. Developers don’t directly access APIs, They subscribe to a Product.
            -> Example: Product: E-commerce APIs. It includes:
                -> Order API
                -> Payment API
                -> User API
            -> Type of Product:
                -> Open Product: In this no subscription will be required and anyone can use APIs
                -> Protected Product: It require subscription and needs API keys

    -> Main Components:
        -> API Gateway:
            -> Entry point for all API requests. When a client calls an API:
                -> Request first goes to API Gateway
                -> Gateway processes it
                -> Then forward it to backend
            -> Responsibilities of API Gateway:
                -> Route requests to backend services
                -> Validate API keys / authentication
                -> Apply rate limiting and quotas
                -> Transform request/response (XML ↔ JSON)
                -> Cache responses
                -> Generate logs and metrics

        -> Management Plane:
            -> Admin interface to manage APIs. This is used by admins (you) to configure APIM.
            -> Used for:
                -> Configure API Management service
                -> Create or import APIs
                -> Create products
                -> Apply policies (rate limit, transform)
                -> Monitor analytics
                -> Manage users

        -> Developer Portal:
            -> UI for developers to use APIs. This is for external developers (API consumers)
            -> Features:
                -> View API documentation
                -> Test APIs (interactive console)
                -> Subscribe to products
                -> Get API keys
                -> Track usage
                -> Think of it like self service website for developer.

        -> Products: Refer Core Concept in APIM

        -> Groups: Groups are used for access control.
            -> System Groups:
                -> Administrators:
                    -> Manage APIs and APIM instance. Full control over APIM
                -> Developers:
                    -> Authenticated users who consume APIs or Registered users who use APIs
                -> Guests:
                    -> Unauthenticated users (read-only access)
            -> Custom Groups:
                -> Can be created by admin
                -> Can integrate with Entra ID groups

        -> Developers:
            -> Represents user accounts in APIM
            -> Can:
                -> Join via portal or invitation
                -> Belong to groups
                -> Subscribe to products
                -> Get API keys

        -> Policies:
            -> Definition:
                -> Rules applied on API requests/responses
            -> Common Use Cases:
                -> Rate limiting
                -> Request/response transformation
                -> Authentication/authorization
                -> Caching

            -> Execution:
                -> Policies run sequentially

            -> Scope Levels:
                -> Global (all APIs)
                -> Product level
                -> API level
                -> Operation level

            -> Policy Expressions:
                -> Used for dynamic logic inside policies

        -> Key Flow:
            -> Developer subscribes to a Product
            -> Gets an API Key
            -> Calls API via Gateway
            -> Request hit API Gateway.
            -> Gateway validate the request and applies policies
            -> Request goes to backend service.
            -> Response comes via Gateway
            -> gateway may transform/cache response
            -> Final response sent to the client.

=> API Management (3scale-style Understanding)
    -> High-Level Architecture:
        -> Product = Entry Layer (what developers see and subscribe to)
        -> Backend = Actual API implementation (your service)
        -> Policies = Control & security rules
        -> Audience = Who can access
    -> Flow:
        Product
           ├── Policies (CORS, Security, Rate Limit)
           ├── Backend(s) (Actual APIs)
           ├── Mapping Rules (Routing logic)
           └── Audience (Access control)

        Developer
           ↓
        Subscribes to Product
           ↓
        Gets API Key
           ↓
        Calls API
           ↓
        Gateway applies:
           - Policies
           - Mapping Rules
           ↓
        Request goes to Backend

    -> Comparison with Azure APIM
        | 3scale Concept | Azure Equivalent     |
        | -------------- | -------------------- |
        | Product        | Product              |
        | Backend        | Backend/API          |
        | Mapping Rules  | Routing + Policies   |
        | Audience       | Groups + Products    |
        | Policies       | Policies (XML-based) |

=> Azure API Management (APIM)

    -> API Gateway (Data Plane / Runtime):

        -> Definition:
            -> API Gateway is the core component responsible for handling all API requests.
            -> It acts as a reverse proxy between client and backend services.
            -> Also known as Data Plane or Runtime.

        -> Key Responsibility:
            -> Receives client request
            -> Applies policies (security, rate limit, transformation)
            -> Routes request to correct backend service
            -> Sends response back to client
            -> Collects logs and telemetry

    -> Problem Without API Gateway:

        -> If clients directly call backend services:

            -> Complex Client Code:
                -> Client must track multiple endpoints
                -> Must handle failures manually

            -> Tight Coupling:
                -> Client depends on backend structure
                -> If backend changes -> client must change

            -> Multiple Calls for Single Operation:
                -> One request may require calling multiple services

            -> Repeated Responsibilities:
                -> Each service must handle:
                    -> Authentication
                    -> SSL termination
                    -> Rate limiting

            -> Security Risk:
                -> Each service is exposed publicly
                -> Increases attack surface

    -> How API Gateway Solves These Problems:

        -> Acts as single entry point for all requests
        -> Decouples client from backend services
        -> Handles cross-cutting concerns:
            -> Authentication
            -> SSL termination
            -> Rate limiting
            -> Logging and monitoring

    -> Managed vs Self-Hosted Gateway:

        -> Managed Gateway:
            -> Default gateway provided by Azure
            -> Deployed in Azure cloud
            -> All API traffic flows through Azure
            -> Used when backend is in cloud or accessible via internet

        -> Self-Hosted Gateway:
            -> Container-based gateway (Docker supported)
            -> Can run on:
                -> On-premise servers
                -> Other cloud providers
            -> Used in hybrid or multi-cloud scenarios
            -> Still managed from central APIM instance

